Problem definition¶

Sales forecasting is the process of predicting how much revenue a company, team, or person will generate within a specific timeframe. Every organization or company wants to make an accurate and valid sales forecast because it is very helpful in making many decisions. An accurate sales forecast allows and helps companies to efficiently allocate resources for their future growth and manage their cash flow.

Sales forecasting is both a science and an art. Decision makers rely on these forecasts to plan for business expansion and to determine how to fuel the company’s growth. So, in many ways, sales forecasting affects everyone in the organization

Removing these outliers will be good for the models to perform well on the data.

In [25]:
def remove_outliers(data, col):
    third_quartile = np.quantile(data[col], 0.75)
    first_quartile = np.quantile(data[col], 0.25)
    inter_quartile_range = third_quartile - first_quartile
 
    print("IQR value for column %s is: %s" % (col, inter_quartile_range))
    global outlier_free_list
    global filtered_data
    
    lower_range = first_quartile - 1.5 * inter_quartile_range
    upper_range = third_quartile + 1.5 * inter_quartile_range
    outlier_free_list = [x for x in data[col] if ((x > lower_range) & (x < upper_range))]
    filtered_data = data.loc[data[col].isin(outlier_free_list)]
    
    return filtered_data

Preparing Data for Modeling¶

As we already know that computers or machines can't interpret or understand textual or categorical data. Therefore, converting the categorical features to numerical ones are must so that the computer can process it and the data is in a valid form for the algorithm to be fitted upon. Converting the categorical columns to numberical by changing it's type to category and then applying some category codes to it.

For the numerical data, we have to apply some normalization technique because the range of the features vary too much from each other i.e. the maximum value of column Product_Allocated_Area is 0.298 where as the maximum value of column Product_Store_Sales_Total is just 8000. So there differences in the range of columns can cause problems while training a machine learning model i.e. the model will assume the feature with high values as more important than the other ones can't be true all the time.

so to avoid that we are applying min_max normalization technique to bring all the data to the range (0, 1).
